g the cartoons submitted to the Cartoon Contest Climate Change in Asia-Pacific -organized in 2012 by the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Human Development Report Unit, UNDP Asia-Pacific Regional Centre. Layout and design by Ryce Chanchai This publication compiles the contributions made by the Asia-Pacific Inclusive Growth and Development Network members in their individual capacities to the moderated e-discussion on Advancing Sustainable Development: The Case of Extractive Industries. Some modifications may be observed in comparison to the original contributions available online to ensure consistency of format. The e-discussion does not necessarily reflect the views of the United Nations Development Programme, its Executive Board or its Member States. UNDP accepts no responsibility for the veracity or authenticity of the messages posted on the Network or in the consolidated reply. TABLE OF CONTENTS Introduction Executive Summary Synthesis Launch Message The AP-IGD network received responses with thanks from: Rui Gomes, Timor- Carl Bruch, Question on checks and balances of Petroleum Fund withdrawals Rui Gomes, Checks and balances are not a guarantee Taimur Khilji, Addressing macro concerns? Glenn Banks, Revenue stabilization, regulatory frameworks and capacity: Some observations of the Papua New Guinea case Yanchun Zhang, Natural resource revenue collection in the context of increasing commodity price volatility Satoru Araki, Yanchun Zhang, Follow up on using market-based risk management instruments to hedge against price swings Amarendra Das, Investment in human capital and community participation in monitoring mining activities Dorji Choden, Strong regulation and enforcement mechanisms to maximize environmental sustainability and social benefit Kishan Khoday, Social accountability pivotal to achieving inclusive, green growth in the extractive sector Robert Goodland, The sustainability issue in EI Robert Goodland, The sustainability issue in EI Glenn Bank